    <h1>The 70s</h1>
    <img src="images/ALPINE.jpg" width="500" />
    <h2>The Beginning</h2>
    <p>The World Rally Championship began in 1973 as the first global championship for rally manufacturers. Throughout the 1970s, it featured long and demanding rallies on snow, gravel,
        and rough roads across the world. Major manufacturers such as Ford Motor Company, Fiat, and Alpine competed in famous events like the Monte Carlo Rally and the Safari Rally, helping establish rally racing as one of the toughest forms of motorsport. But one team really stood out:</p>
    <h2>LANCIA</h2>
    <h3> And the Stratos HF</h3>
    <img src="images/stratos.jpg" width="600"/>
    <p>In the mid-1970s, Lancia dominated the WRC with the purpose-built Lancia Stratos HF, a car designed specifically for rally racing rather than adapted from a road car.
        Powered by a V6 engine from Ferrari and driven by champions like Sandro Munari, the Stratos won three consecutive manufacturers’ titles from 1974 to 1976 and became one of the most iconic rally cars ever built.</p>
